name: How a processor works
description: We will describe how the program's instructions are executed out-of-order in a current processor microarchitecture.

steps.title: Microarchitecture of the Execution Engine of a processor
steps.description: Look at the main components of the microarchitecture of the Execution Engine of a current processor. Next, I will ask you some questions. First, select the "B2" processor configuration.

validation.message: You must select the "B2" processor configuration on the top-left panel

steps.title: Waiting Buffer
steps.questionText: ‚ùìWhy do instructions need to wait in the Waiting Buffer before execution?

answers.text: Due to unresolved data dependencies with preceding instructions
answers.explanation: ‚ùå Partially correct. You've correctly identified data dependencies as one reason! When an instruction depends on results from a previous instruction that hasn't completed, it must wait. This creates a hazard in the pipeline where the consumer instruction stalls until the producer provides its output.

answers.text: It's a random occurrence in the processor
answers.explanation: ‚ùå Incorrect. Processor behavior is never random‚Äîit follows deterministic rules based on instruction dependencies, resource availability, and scheduling algorithms. The waiting buffer exists for specific, predictable reasons related to pipeline efficiency.

answers.text: Due to execution port contention (all ports are busy)
answers.explanation: ‚ùå Partially correct. Good observation about port contention! Modern processors have multiple execution ports (ALUs, FPUs, etc.), but each port can only handle one instruction per cycle. When multiple ready instructions compete for the same port type, some must wait‚Äîthis is called structural hazard.

answers.text: Both data dependencies and execution port contention
answers.explanation: ‚úÖ Excellent! You've identified both critical factors: Data Dependencies (Data Hazards) Instructions wait when they need results from preceding instructions that haven't completed. The pipeline must enforce proper execution order to ensure data flows correctly. Execution Port Contention (Structural Hazards) Even when instructions are data-ready, they may wait if all compatible execution ports are busy. Each port type (integer, floating-point, memory) has limited capacity, creating bottlenecks.

steps.title: Summary
steps.description:
üí°Data dependencies create an execution ordering constraint: the consumer instruction cannot proceed until the producer instruction has completed. This is necessary because data must physically travel from the output stage of one execution unit to the input stage of another‚Äîand yes, sometimes both operations use the same execution port!

The waiting buffer serves as a scheduling queue that:

(1) Resolves dependencies by tracking which operands are ready (2) Manages port allocation to maximize utilization (3) Enables out-of-order execution when dependencies allow (4) Reduces pipeline bubbles by keeping instructions ready for dispatch

Real-world analogy: Think of it like a restaurant kitchen‚Äîsome dishes wait because ingredients aren't ready (data dependencies), while others wait because all stoves are busy (port contention).
